An Emergency Response Program has been developed to respond to any chlorine release scenario. Emergency response actions involve the system operators and maintenance staff, the Base Fire Department, and off-site expertise from the San Diego County Hazardous Incident Response Team (HIRT), when necessary. In addition, the Assistant Chief of Staff, Environmental Security (AC/S, Env Scty) or an appointed representative serves as the focal point for notifying the appropriate agencies and providing information to the public.

1.2    STATIONARY SOURCE AND REGULATED SUBSTANCES HANDLED
Chlorine stored in 150-pound cylinders and one-ton containers is used for disinfection at wastewater treatment facilities under Risk Management Plan (RMP) Program Level 3. The one-ton containers have an administrative fill limit of 1,200 pounds. Table 1-1 identifies Program Level 3 chlorine facilities at MCB Camp Pendleton, provides a description of the process, and lists the maximum amount of chlorine in the system.  Facilities that have been removed from the revised RMP are listed in Table 1-2.  Other chlorine facilities exist at MCB Camp Pendleton and they are described in two other RMP Public Documents - Program Levels 1 and 2.

Table 1-1. Summary of Program Level 3 Chlorine Systems
Building/ Process Number        Process Description        Maximum Quantity (pounds)
17831        Sewage Treatment Plant (STP) 2: One 1-ton container on-line, two 150-lb cylinders stand-by,

 two 1-ton containers in storage (1,200-lb fill each)        3,900
20831        STP 13: One 1-ton containers on-line, one 1-ton container stand-by, four 1-ton containers in storage (1,200-lb fill each) with scrubber        7,200

Table 1-2. Chlorine Systems Removed from RMP Program Level 3
Building/ Process Number        Process Description        Reason Removed
22831        STP 3: Two 1-ton containers on-line, two 150-lb cylinders in storage        System changed to 150-pound cylinders, 600 pounds on site; changed to Program Level 1 and de-registered from EPA RMP program 

1.3    WORST-CASE RELEASE SCENARIO(S) AND ALTERNATIVE RELEASE SCENARIO(S)
The site-specific worst-case release analysis and alternative release scenario are on file at MCB Camp Pendleton.

1.4    GENERAL ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM AND THE SPECIFIC PREVENTION STEPS
MCB Camp Pendleton has taken steps so that the chlorine systems comply with EPA?s Accidental Release Prevention Rule and with applicable state codes and regulations. The buildings containing the systems have been evaluated against NFPA 55 and the Uniform Building Code. As a result, several system or building upgrades are being planned or considered (see Section 1.7 for more details).
MCB Camp Pendleton has developed a prevention program that includes the following elements:
?    Documenting process safety information regarding the hazards of chlorine and components of the system;
?    Conducting a PHA to evaluate potential mechanical failures or operational causes that could result in an accidental release;
?    Implementing written standard operating procedures;
?    Implementing a staff training program;
?    Implementing a mechanical integrity (preventive maintenance) program;
?    Implementing Management of Change procedures;
?    Conducting a pre-startup review;
?    Conducting compliance audits;
?    Conducting incident investigations;
?    Implementing an employee participation program; 
?    Implementing a hot work permit program; and
?    Implementing a contractor safety program.

